#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:1
msgid "Already installed Rust?"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:3
msgid ""
"Other package managers also ship Rust, and you may wish to use the packaged "
"toolchain, such as for distribution package development. You may also wish "
"to use a `rustup`\\-managed toolchain such as nightly or beta. Normally, "
"`rustup` will complain that you already have Rust installed in `/usr` and "
"refuse to install. However, you can install Rust via `rustup` and have it "
"coexist with your packaged Rust toolchain."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:10
msgid "Set up rustup with an existing Rust toolchain"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:12
msgid ""
"When you initially install Rust with `rustup`, pass the `-y` option to make "
"it ignore the packaged Rust toolchain and install a `rustup`\\-managed "
"toolchain into `~/.cargo/bin`. Add that directory to your `$PATH` (or let "
"`rustup` do it for you by not passing `--no-modify-path`). Then, to tell "
"`rustup` about your system toolchain, run:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:22
msgid ""
"You can then use \"system\" as a `rustup` toolchain, just like \"nightly\". "
"For example, using the [toolchain override shorthand](../overrides."
"md#toolchain-override-shorthand), you can run `cargo +system build` to build "
"with the system toolchain, or `cargo +nightly build` to build with nightly."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:26
msgid ""
"If you wish to develop with the system toolchain (e.g. for distribution "
"packages), you may want to make it your [default toolchain](../overrides."
"md#default-toolchain):"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:33
msgid "Ensure the correct `$PATH` configuration"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:35
msgid ""
"There are times when the above steps don't work, and you may see strange "
"error messages when running commands that should have been proxied by "
"rustup. For example, when running `cargo +stable --version`, you may "
"encounter the following error:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:47
msgid ""
"This means `cargo` is currently not a `rustup` proxy, and your `$PATH` needs "
"to be fixed."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:50
msgid ""
"In fact, on any machine with rustup installed, you would like to have "
"**rustup proxies showing up first in `$PATH`**, shadowing any other Rust "
"installations. Don't worry: these shadowed installations can then be adopted "
"by rustup with the `rustup toolchain link` command as mentioned above."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:55
msgid ""
"The exact steps to be taken to make rustup proxies come first may vary "
"according to your system environment, but usually it is about changing the "
"evaluation order of certain lines in your shell configuration file(s)."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:59
msgid ""
"To make it clearer, let's look at the example of a Mac with both regular "
"rustup fetched from [rustup.rs](https://rustup.rs) and homebrew-installed "
"`rust`. The **right way** to configure `.profile` in this environment would "
"be:"
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:68
msgid ""
"In this example, both of these lines _prepend_ to `$PATH`, so the last one "
"takes over, letting the rustup proxies shadow the homebrew-installed `rust`. "
"On the other hand, putting these lines the other way around will cause the "
"aforementioned error."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:73
msgid ""
"When in doubt, you can always debug your shell configuration by printing the "
"status of your current `$PATH` with `echo $PATH | xargs -n1` and paying "
"attention to the order of `$CARGO_HOME/bin` (which defaults to `$HOME/.cargo/"
"bin`) compared to your package manager's `bin` directory."
msgstr ""

#: src/installation/already-installed-rust.md:78
msgid ""
